{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.1 Disease Response Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Eisenhauer EA, Therasse P, Bogaerts J, et al. New response evaluation criteria in solid tumours: revised RECIST guideline (version 1.1). Eur J Cancer. 2009;45(2):228-247. doi:10.1016/j.ejca.2008.10.026","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.1 Disease Response Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Cheson BD, Fisher RI, Barrington SF, et al. Recommendations for initial evaluation, staging, and response assessment of Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphoma: the Lugano classification. J Clin Oncol. 2014;32(27):3059-3068. doi:10.1200/JCO.2013.54.8800","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3 Disease Response and Clinical Classifications (RS)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","heading_level":5,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"RS – Clinical Classifications Use Case Assumptions","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":1,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The following assumptions are unique to the RS domain clinical classifications use case:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Clinical classifications are named instruments whose output is an ordinal or categorical score that serves as a surrogate for or ranking of disease status or other physiological or biological status.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Clinical classifications may be based solely on objective data from clinical records, or they may involve a clinical judgment or interpretation of directly observable signs, behaviors, or other physical manifestations related to a condition or subject status. These physical manifestations may be findings (e.g., lab results, vital signs, clinical events) that are typically represented in other SDTM domains.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"RSCAT is used to group a set of assessments based on a clinical classification. One of the codelists for RSCAT is CCCAT. The CCCAT codelist contains CDISC Controlled Terminology for clinical classifications instruments.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0336_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":336,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"When using the RS domain to represent a clinical classification instrument that incorporates data from other domains:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Whenever possible, all source data must be represented in the topic-based domain(s) to which they pertain. For example, if a lab test value is collected and then scored for a response evaluation or clinical classification instrument, the lab test value must be recorded in the LB domain using the rules that apply to that domain and the tests being represented.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"If the source value is directly collected on the clinical classification instrument, then the values from the source record may be transcribed to the corresponding RS record, with RSORRES and RSORRESRU populated to agree with the units shown on the clinical classification instrument, which may be different from the sponsor's usual practice or original and standard units.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"If a clinical classification uses a source value by comparing it to a range (e.g., \"2-5\", \">-3\"), then the source value will exist only in the source domain; the range is represented in the corresponding RS record in RSORRES and RSORRESRU.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.9.3.2 Clinical Classifications Use Case","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"In all cases, RSSTRESC/RSSTRESN should be populated with the assigned ordinal score as indicated on the instrument.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The following assumptions are common to the FT and QS domains as well as the Clinical Classifications use case of the RS domain (not the Disease Response use case of RS):","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The name of a QRS instrument is described under the variable --CAT in the relevant QRS domain (i.e., FT, QS, RS), and may be either abbreviations or longer names. For example, \"ADAS-Cog\", \"BPI SHORT FORM\", and \"APACHE II\" are all --CATs which are shortened names for the instruments they represent, whereas \"al STAIR ASCEND\" is the FTCAT for the instrument of the same name. Sponsors should always reference CDISC Controlled Terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The QRS Naming Rules for --CAT, --TEST, and --TESTCD and the list of QRS instruments that have published CDISC Controlled Terminology with NCI/EVS are available at: https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/terminology/controlled-terminology"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Refer to the following CDISC Controlled Terminology codelists for QRS instrument --CAT terminology:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Category of Clinical Classification","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Category of Functional Test","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Category of Questionnaire","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"QRS --TESTCD/--TEST terminology codelists are listed separately by instrument name.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Names of subcategories for groups of items/questions are described under the --SCAT variable.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"--SCAT values are not included in the CDISC Controlled Terminology system but rather controlled as described in the QRS supplements in which they are used.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"There are cases where QRS CRFs do not include numeric \"standardized responses\" assigned to text responses (e.g., mild, moderate, severe being 1, 2, 3). It is clearly in everyone's best interest to include the numeric \"standardized responses\" in the SDTMIG QRS dataset. This is only done when the numeric \"standardized response\" are documented in the QRS CRF instructions, a user manual, a website specific to the QRS instrument, or another reference document that provides a clear explanation and rationale for providing them in the SDTMIG QRS dataset.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0337_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":337,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Sponsors should always consult published QRS supplements for guidance on submitting derived information in a SDTMIG QRS domain. Derived variable results in QRS are usually considered captured data. If sponsors operationally derive variable results, then the derived records that are submitted in a QRS domain should be flagged by --DRVFL.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The following rules apply for \"total\"-type scores in QRS datasets.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The QRS instrument subtotal or total score, which is the sum of the numeric responses for an instrument, is populated in --ORRES, --STRESC, and --STRESN. It is considered a captured subtotal or total score without any knowledge of the sponsor's case management process reduced to the score.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"If operationally derived by the sponsor, it is the sponsor's responsibility to set the --DRVFL flag based on their cRF process to derive subtotal and total scores. An investigator-derived score written on a CRF will be considered a captured score and will not be flagged. When subtotal and total scores are received from a central provider or vendor, the value would go into --ORRES and --DRVFL would be null (see Section 4.1.8.1, Origin Metadata for Variables).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["Section 4.1.8.1, Origin Metadata for Variables"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a004","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The variable --REPNUM variable is populated when there are multiple repeats of the same question. When records are related to the first trial of the question, the variable --REPNUM should be set to \"1\". When records are related to the second trial of the same question, --REPNUM should be set to \"2\", and so forth.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a005","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The actual version number of an instrument is represented in the --CAT value as designated by the QRS Terminology Team. If it is determined that this is not the case for an instrument:","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a006","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Notify the QRS Terminology Team that the instrument has a specific or multiple version numbers. This team will assist in providing an resolution on how the situation will be handled.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Consider the use of the --GRPID variable to indicate the instrument's version number prior to a decision by the QRS Terminology Team.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The sponsor is expected to provide information about the version used for each QRS instrument in the metadata (using the Comments column in the Define-XML document). This could be provided as value-level metadata for --CAT.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The sponsor is expected to provide information about the scoring rules in the metadata.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"If the variable --TEST is represented with verbatim text >40 characters, represent the abbreviated meaningful text in --TEST within 40 characters and describe the full text of the item in the study metadata. If the verbatim item in the study metadata. If the verbatim item text in the study metadata is >200 characters, represent the abbreviated meaningful text in SSORRES within the 200 characters and describe the full text in the study metadata; see Section 4.5.3, Text Strings that Exceed the Maximum Length for General Observation-class Findings. For further information.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["Section 4.5.3, Text Strings that Exceed the Maximum Length for General Observation-class Findings"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"The instrument's annotated CRF can also be used as a reference for the full text in both of these situations.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"--EVAL and --EVALID must not be used to model QRS data in SDTM. These variables have had various interpretations on QRS CRFs and were used to represent a multitude of evaluator information about QRS instruments. This has made it more difficult for users of SDTM QRS data to interpret this data and more difficult to pool data for analyses. If needed, supplemental qualifiers may be used to represent this data. Updated information on a proposed solution to this issue will be posted on the CDISC QRS webpage (https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"All standard QRS supplement development is coordinated with the CDISC SDS QRS Subteam as the governing body. The process involves drafting the controlled terminology and defining instrument-specific standardized value for qualifier, timing, and result variables to populate the SDTMIG for FT, QS, and RS domains. These supplements are developed based on user demand and therapeutic area standards development needs. Sponsors should always consult the CDISC website to review the terminology and supplements prior to modeling any QRS instruments.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Sponsors may participate and/or request the development of additional QRS supplements and terminology through the CDISC SDS QRS subteam and the Controlled Terminology QRS subteam.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0338_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":338,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Once generated, the QRS supplement is posted on the CDISC website (https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":["https://www.cdisc.org/standards/foundational/qrs"],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0339_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":339,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3 [MODELS FOR FINDINGS DOMAINS]","atom_type":"LIST_ITEM","verbatim":"Any identifiers, timing variables, or findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to any QRS domain. In general, identifiers should be considered generated observation class qualifiers that are generally not used: --POS, --BODYSYS, --ORNRLO, --ORNRHI, --STNRLO, --STNRHI, --STRNC, --NRIND, --XFN, --LOINC, --SPEC, --SPCCND, --LOC, --FAST, --TOX, --TOXGR, --SEV.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.3","ts":"2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
